04625nam a22005415i 9780674249684DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742496847 a10.4159/97806742496842doi  a(DE-B1597)572206  a(OCoLC)1196194730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aLB1028.3b.R4375 2020eb 7aEDU0390002bisacsh04a371.332231 aReich, Justin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFailure to Disrupt :bWhy Technology Alone Can’t Transform Education /cJustin Reich. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction: Education Technology’s Unrequited Disruption -- tPart I : Three Genres of Learning at Scale -- t1. Instructor-Guided Learning at Scale: Massive Open Online Courses -- t2. Algorithm-Guided Learning at Scale: Adaptive Tutors and Computer-Assisted Instruction -- t3. Peer-Guided Learning at Scale: Networked Learning Communities -- t4. Testing the Genres of Learning at Scale: Learning Games -- tPart II: Dilemmas in Learning at Scale -- t5. The Curse of the Familiar -- t6. The Edtech Matthew Effect -- t7. The Trap of Routine Assessment -- t8. The Toxic Power of Data and Experiments -- tConclusion: Preparing for the Next Learning-at- Scale Hype Cycle -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA leader in educational technology separates truth from hype, explaining what tech can—and can’t—do to transform our classrooms.Proponents of large-scale learning have boldly promised that technology can disrupt traditional approaches to schooling, radically accelerating learning and democratizing education. Much-publicized experiments, often underwritten by Silicon Valley entrepreneurs, have been launched at elite universities and in elementary schools in the poorest neighborhoods. Such was the excitement that, in 2012, the New York Times declared the “year of the MOOC.” Less than a decade later, that pronouncement seems premature.In Failure to Disrupt: Why Technology Alone Can’t Transform Education, Justin Reich delivers a sobering report card on the latest supposedly transformative educational technologies. Reich takes readers on a tour of MOOCs, autograders, computerized “intelligent tutors,” and other educational technologies whose problems and paradoxes have bedeviled educators. Learning technologies—even those that are free to access—often provide the greatest benefit to affluent students and do little to combat growing inequality in education. And institutions and investors often favor programs that scale up quickly, but at the expense of true innovation. It turns out that technology cannot by itself disrupt education or provide shortcuts past the hard road of institutional change.Technology does have a crucial role to play in the future of education, Reich concludes. We still need new teaching tools, and classroom experimentation should be encouraged. But successful reform efforts will focus on incremental improvements, not the next killer app.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aComputer-assisted instructionxEvaluation. 0aEducational change. 0aEducational technology. 0aInternet in educationxEvaluation. 0aMOOCs (Web-based instruction)xEvaluation. 7aEDUCATION / Computers & Technology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067424968440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674249684423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674249684.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harv